On Atriplex spinifera shrubs near Soda Lake.

Thallus mostly absent. Apothecia abundant, often crowded, round to folded, raised off substrate and nearly stipitate, rims white pruinose, cracked, disks translucent pale to green to peach and then darkening but not black, eprunose. Amphithecum thick with algae, with a thick cortex of round cells20-30µm extending down and around the base of the apothecia, POL+ soluble crystals in the pigmented cortex, not in medulla tissue. Paraphyses rather thick, 2-3µm, brached distally.

Spores simple, hyaline, ellipsoid. 9.9×3.6

results.notes:
A NJMA foray collections made by club members Marti B. and Linda.
The colors are accurate. The mushrooms had a disagreeable odor. Nina Burghardt took this mushroom home and studied it microscopically. Somehow she came up with C. caesiifolius, but I have doubts that it’s what we have here based on the online info.
This collection was preserved and will eventually be sequenced.
DNA Sequencing Results & Discussion (posted on 24-Nov-23):
Steve Russell (SDR) obtained a full-length nrITS sequence from this material via ONT-nanopore sequencing. RiC (reads in consensus) = 267. This sequence is a 99.5-99.8% match to 11 GenBank accessions labeled C. alboluteus and C. lewisii, including the TYPE sequence of the former. C. alboluteus is a junior synonym of C. lewisii, although the type sequence of lewisii is still not in GenBank.

results.notes:
A NJMA foray collection.
I found these small, dainty and fragile grisettes growing on the side of one of the many trails arranged in a street grid in the park, but cannot remember where exactly. The habitat is the typical pine-oak barrens of southern NJ. Given their fresh, not waterlogged condition, they must have grown immediately after it had rained during the night/early morning. It’s been quite dry in the area prior to this rain event, so I am sure they grew in response to that rain.
Compare with the morphologically similar, yet large and robust, series Ceciliae of obs 478445 also found at this foray.
The morphology can be inferred from the photos. Notably, the plentiful UV deposits on the cap consist of these dark brown to black subpyramidal to pyramidal warts, and the UV remnants and limbus internus on the stipe are also dark gray. I have never seen such a species in the NJ Pine Barrens, or elsewhere, but it could be one of RET’s provisionally named entities. Also compare with Y. Lamoureux’s ubiquitous A. rhacopus that could be absent from the outer Atlantic coastal plain.
The larger fruitbody had the following dimension:
Overall height 6.5 cm. Cap with a 4 cm wide footprint; marginal striations up to 0.26R. Gills 4.5 mm wide. Stipe 6.1 cm long, 0.6 cm wide at apex and gradually widening to 1.1 cm at the base; central canal/cylinder 0.4~0.86 cm wide, stuffed with sparse cottony deposits forming chambers in the uppers part of stipe.
This collection was preserved and sampled for DNA (ITS).

results.notes:
A NJMA foray collection.
I found this sorry-looking, damaged and a bit waterlogged sect. Vaginatae somewhere in a grid of trails in the park. The habitat is a typical Pine Barrens setting of scrub oak & pitch pines. It was already knocked over (by wildlife or hikers), laying in grass and leaf litter with a broken off and severed stipe, and apparently exhibiting heliotropism. It must have grown overnight in response to a rain event drenching the dry woods 8-10 hours before the foray. The cap color and the single gray patch of volva on the cap suggest A. xanthomitra – a member of series Ceciliae, as per RET. Apparently common and known to cover the entire range of the eastern seaboard (numerous sequenced collections from ME to FL), having been collected from NJ and occurring as far west as Michigan (obs 329539), xanthomitra is, nonetheless, a new grisette species to me.
The collection was saved.
DNA sequencing results and discussion (posted 8-May-22):
This collection was sampled for ITS. There are two points of heterogeneity in ITS1 separated by a considerable number of bases (ca. 45 bps), as deduced from the two reads. The heterogeneity pattern in the forward read cannot be resolved. The heterogeneity pattern in the reverse read appears to be a 2-base frameshift, but resolving this pattern manually to separate the 2 haplotypes is very difficult and was not attempted due to a high probability of error making. Hence, the stretch of ITS1 obscured by the heteromorphy cannot be resolved and the reads cannot be bridged together. Unfortunately, the legible portion of the forward read is only 132 characters long, which is too short for publication in GenBank. On the other hand, the reverse read, consisting of the last 10 bps of ITS1 followed by complete 5.8S and ITS2 regions and the first 21 bases of LSU, is overall 351 bps long and will be submitted to GenBank. The reverse read is now posted to this observation.

results.notes:
A NJMA foray collections made by several club members, myself included.
I used Tom Volk’s website & paper and successfully keyed out this Honey Mushroom to Armillaria gallica. The salient morphological features of gallica — all present in our mushrooms — are:
1) Growing terrestrially singly, not gregariously, in soil (not on trees)
2) Hairy (not scaly) pinkish-brown caps
3) Cortinaceous partial veil, leaving a white “arachnoid” ring zone
4) Swollen stipe base, staining yellow where bruised

The look-alike is A. calvescens, but it has a more northern distribution and often grows in large non-caespitose troops.

results.notes:
A NJMA foray collection. A caespitose cluster of four small basidiomata found by Maricel Patino in an unremarkable habitat, typical of the NJ Pine Barrens. She showed me the spot — a small exposed sandy “island” on the edge of woods next to the main parking lot with only pitch pines in the immediate vicinity, with some shrubby scrub oak some 8-10 yards away; no white pines or any other kind of conifers. The mushrooms were growing at the base of a medium-sized P. rigida in the middle of the “island”.
The morphology can be inferred from the photos. The salient features of this species that I cannot match to any known eastern/northeastern Suillus are the combination of a dry and scaly cap, lack of a partial veil or velar remnants, and plentiful orange-brown glandular dots merging into large glandular smears on a bald whitish/pale cream background. The only species resembles somewhat is the hardwood-associated S. subaureus.
This collection was preserved and submitted for DNA sequencing (ITS).

An unusual sect. Lepidella species that is totally new to me. The fruitobody odor was that of a musty cellar (probably because the mushroom was slightly waterlogged?).
This collection is preserved and will eventually be sequenced.

DNA Sequencing Results & Discussion (posted on 24-Nov-23):
The derived full-length nrITS sequence (ONT-nanopore by Steve Russell) is 99.3-100% similar to 7 GenBank accessions, including the one associated with obs 440126 (see trees posted there). These sequences are mostly labeled as “Tricholoma aff. sejunctum” and the associated collections are all from the USA (NY, NJ, IN, TN and FL).
The Canadian accessions associated with the large MycoQuebec study of Tricoloma and labeled as “Tricholoma subsejuncum” are 98.2% similar. Alignment of the present ITS sequence with those of subsejunctum sensu MycoQuebec shows that all the mismatching positions (11) are due to gaps and all but one are associated with an indel event in ITS1 (the Canadian sequences are longer). The Canadian accessions are also identical to 2 GenBank sequences derived from Nova Scotia collections recorded on MO (obs 496082 and obs 496470). If the USA & Canadian entities are conspecific, then there is a clear continental phylogeographic divide, probably related to glaciation event(s).
The large ITS tree of sect. Tricholoma on p. 19 in the MycoQuebec opus shows a moderately supported clade (bootstrap support of 65%) that includes accessions of T. subsejunctum & T. subluteum sensu MycoQuebec, as well as the holotypes of T. atrofibrillosum (Alaska), T. sinoportentosum (China) and T. olivaceoluteolum (China). Peck’s type of T. subsejunctum was sampled but failed to yield a sequence (see p. 29 of the MQ study). Such old collections with highly fragmented DNA require whole genome sequencing using modern methodologies.
